beenthere.description: For nearly 5,000 years, people have lived in these canyons - longer than anyone has lived uninterrupted anywhere on the Colorado Plateau. In the place called Tsegi, their homes and images tell us their stories. Today, Navajo families make their homes, raise livestock, and farm the lands in the canyons. A place like no other, the park and Navajo Nation work together to manage the land's resources.

images.caption: Ancient Puebloans built villages like White House that offered opportunities for trade, ceremony, and social gatherings.

beenthere.description: The great Outer Beach described by Thoreau in the 1800s is protected within the national seashore. Forty miles of pristine sandy beach, marshes, ponds, and uplands support diverse species. Lighthouses, cultural landscapes, and wild cranberry bogs offer a glimpse of Cape Cod's past and continuing ways of life. Swimming beaches and walking and biking trails beckon today's visitors.

images.title: Sunrise Waves
images.altText: A curling wave breaks against the backdrop of a pink sunrise.
images.caption: Visiting the beach to watch the sunrise over the Atlantic Ocean is a beautiful experience.

images.title: Sand Ripples
images.altText: Low tide exposes rippled ridges of sand and water.
images.caption: You will never walk the same beach twice on Cape Cod; daily low and high tides expose and then cover the sand.

images.title: Exploring the Park by Water
images.altText: A red kayak floats on a pond facing a forest colored with red and orange leaves.
images.caption: Exploring the park by water offers a different perspective.

images.title: Birds and Beach
images.altText: A flock of birds flies along a beach with waves in the background.
images.caption: The national seashore is known for its species diversity, including threatened and endangered shorebirds.

images.title: Atlantic White Cedar Swamp Trail
images.altText: Boardwalk trail runs through a swamp surrounded by green ferns and tall trees.
images.caption: This popular trail takes visitors through the rare habitat of an Atlantic White Cedar swamp.

images.title: Sunrise Over the Atlantic
images.altText: A brilliant sun rises over the ocean reflecting light on the water's surface.
images.caption: Cape Cod provides the opportunity to watch the sun rise out of the Atlantic Ocean and set into Cape Cod Bay.

beenthere.name: Cape Cod

beenthere.description: North of the Arctic Circle, the monument forms 70 miles of shoreline on the Chukchi Sea. More than 114 beach ridges provide evidence of human use for 5,000 years. The Inupiat continue to use the area today. Vast wetlands provide habitat for shorebirds from as far away as South America. Hikers and boaters can see carpets of wildflowers among shrubs containing wisps of qiviut from muskoxen.

images.title: Muskox and Geese
images.altText: muskox standing on the tundra
images.caption: Muskox and Greater White-fronted Geese on vegetated beach ridges in front of the Igichuk Hills.

images.title: Winter Moon

images.caption: January light and a bright moon at 2 pm over the Igichuk Hills in Cape Krusenstern National Monument.

images.title: Beach Ridges on the Shore of Cape Krusenstern
images.altText: aerial view of beach ridges
images.caption: Beach ridges created by years of wave action during storms can be seen as parallel lines in the fall vegetation covering the old gravel.

images.title: Fish on a Drying Rack
images.altText: fish hanging on rack
images.caption: Pike (left and right) and trout (middle) dry on a rack at a subsistence camp. The slash marks allow more air to circulate and dry the meat more quickly.

images.title: Old House Uncovered
images.altText: archaeologist digging
images.caption: A University of Washington archeology crew conducts research on an old semi-subterranean house along the beach ridges of Cape Krusenstern. Old house timbers are slowly revealed about 4 feet down

beenthere.name: Cape Krusenstern

beenthere.description: Amache, also known as the Granada Relocation Center, near Granada, Colorado was one of ten incarceration sites established by the War Relocation Authority during World War II to unjustly incarcerate Japanese Americans. Over 10,000 people, most American citizens, were incarcerated at Amache from 1942-1945. Amache - a place to reflect, recommit, and further the pursuit of freedom and justice.

images.caption: Reconstructed barracks, guard and water towers at the newly designated Amache National Historic Site

beenthere.description: Established in 1972, Buffalo National River flows freely for 135 miles and is one of the few remaining undammed rivers in the lower 48 states. Once you arrive, prepare to journey from running rapids to quiet pools while surrounded by massive bluffs as you cruise through the Ozark Mountains down to the White River.

images.title: Indian Rockhouse
images.altText: A large bluff shelter near Buffalo Point.
images.caption: Every year thousands of people hike to the Indian Rockhouse to admire this large bluff shelter.

images.caption: A peaceful day on the Buffalo River as kayakers approach Skull Rock and Buffalo Point.

images.caption: Camping along the Buffalo River is a wonderful way to enjoy the park.

images.title: Floating the Buffalo
images.altText: Floaters on the river.
images.caption: Canoeing and kayaking the river is a wonderful way to spend a day at the Buffalo.

images.title: Sod Collier Homestead
images.altText: Historic homestead built by the Collier Family.
images.caption: Many historic structures are scattered along the Buffalo River reminding us of the hardworking settlers that once called this river valley home.

images.title: Smallmouth Bass Fishing
images.altText: Fisherman with smallmouth bass.
images.caption: Fishing for smallmouth bass is a popular activity on the Buffalo River.

beenthere.name: Buffalo

bucketlist.description: . . . where you can walk a Civil War-era fort, visit historic lighthouses, explore tide pools, hike lush trails, camp under the stars, or relax while fishing, picnicking or swimming-all within reach of downtown Boston. bucketlist.description: Home to the National Woman's Party for more than 90 years, this was the epicenter of the struggle for women's rights. From this house in the shadow of the U.S. Capitol and Supreme Court, Alice Paul and the NWP developed innovative strategies and tactics to advocate for the Equal Rights Amendment and equality for women. President Barack Obama designated the national monument on April 12, 2016.

bucketlist.description: Given its remote location and challenging weather conditions, Aniakchak is one of the most wild and least visited places in the National Park System. This landscape is a vibrant reminder of Alaska's location in the volcanically active "Ring of Fire," as it is home to an impressive six mile (10 km) wide, 2,500 ft (762 m) deep caldera formed during a massive volcanic eruption 3,500 years ago.

bucketlist.description: Castle Mountains represents some of the most unique elements of the Mojave Desert. Nestled between the Nevada state line and Mojave National Preserve, the nearly 21,000 acres of Castle Mountains boasts Joshua tree forests, unbroken natural landscapes, rare desert grasslands, and rich human history. This intriguing area provides serenity and solitude from nearby metropolitan areas.

images.title: Red Rocks Outcropping
images.altText: Red rocks frame a stand of Joshua trees and sage brush.
images.caption: Red rocks frame a stand of Joshua trees and sage brush in the desert floor..

images.title: View of Castle Peaks
images.altText: Foreground is desert greenery. The isolated spires of the Castle Peaks rise up in the background
images.caption: From Walking Box Ranch road, visitors to Castle Mountains can enjoy the stunning view of the Castle Peaks, which are located in surrounding Mojave National Preserve lands.

bucketlist.name: Castle Mountains
